											The Hepatitis-B vaccine should not be given if your baby has any severe, life-threatening allergies.<br>
											The Hepatitis-B vaccine can be delayed if your baby:
											</p>

											<ol class="list list-ordened list-ordened-style-2 mb-xlg mt-lg">
												<li>is not feeling well.</li>
												<li>a mild illness, such as a cold</li>
												<li>has fever</li>




											</ol>
										</div>
									</section>

									<section class="toggle">
										<label>Threats</label>
										<div class="toggle-content">
											<p>Avoiding Hepatitis-B vaccine leads to Hepatitis B virus infection. It can be either acute or chronic.<br>
											Acute hepatitis B virus infection is a short-term illness that occurs within the first 6 months after someone is exposed to the hepatitis B virus. This can lead to:
											<ol class="list list-ordened list-ordened-style-2 mb-xlg mt-lg">
												<li>fever, fatigue, loss of appetite, nausea, and/or vomiting</li>
												<li>jaundice (yellow skin or eyes, dark urine, clay-colored bowel movements)</li>
												<li>pain in muscles, joints, and stomach</li>
											</ol>

											Chronic hepatitis B virus infection is a long-term illness that occurs when the hepatitis B virus remains in a person's body.  Most people who go on to develop chronic hepatitis B do not have symptoms, but it is still very serious and can lead to:
											<ol class="list list-ordened list-ordened-style-2 mb-xlg mt-lg">
												<li>liver damage (cirrhosis)</li>
												<li>liver cancer</li>
												<li>death</li>
											</ol>
											</p>
